<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-266-126  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 266 126.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  March 12 1990 n261 p12(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MIS's high fiber diet. (management information systems, fiberdistributed data interface)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McPartlin, John P.; Medina, Diane; Garvey, Martin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The drive by vendors to sell FDDI (fiber distributed datainterface) can be compared to the push to eat oat bran, it wasadvertised as being better for you, but the reality did not matchthe promises.andP;  Oat bran turned out not to be the wonder food forgreater health and longevity, and FDDI may not be the instant,inexpensive cure-all, either.andP;  Forrester Research Inc did a studythat estimates FDDI networks to be at least four years in thefuture (1994), but products being released now by DEC, SunMicrosystems, and IBM may become important later.andP;  Most companieswill appreciate the speed of FDDI, but it also offers better datasecurity, cable durability, and network reliability.andP;  Observers donot think other topologies will disappear, because Ethernet andtoken-ring will fit certain applications better.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber Distributed Data Interface StandardFuture of ComputingMISAnalysisNetwork Management.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographgraph.andO;Caption:   When MIS plans to implement FDDI. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>